  "prompt": "Why don't Indian parents allow their daughter to marry a guy from a different caste?",
  "response": "Caste-based discrimination in India is a complex issue with deep historical and social roots. While not all Indian parents disapprove of inter-caste marriages, here are some of the primary reasons why some do:\n\n*   **Preservation of Caste Identity and Status:** Historically, caste was linked to occupation and social status. Parents may believe that marrying within their caste will preserve their family's social standing, traditions, and perceived purity.\n\n*   **Family Honor and Social Pressure:** In some communities, inter-caste marriage is seen as a violation of tradition and can bring dishonor to the family. This can lead to social ostracization and disapproval from relatives and the wider community.\n\n*   **Concerns about Adjustment and Acceptance:** Parents may worry that their daughter will face discrimination or difficulty adjusting to a new family and community with different customs and values.\n\n*   **Endogamy and Lineage:** Some families prioritize endogamy (marrying within a specific group) to maintain lineage and family ties.\n\n*   **Patriarchal Structures:** Traditional patriarchal structures often give parents, especially fathers, significant control over their children's marriage choices. This can limit a daughter's agency in choosing a partner.\n\nIt's important to recognize that attitudes towards inter-caste marriage are changing in India, particularly among younger generations and in urban areas. There are also legal protections and government initiatives to encourage and support inter-caste marriages.",
